 would make it around the 15th most used language in the United States. %0a%3c %0a%3c ASL is mostly spoken by people who are hearing impaired. However, learning the language in school, even if not to a point of fluency, can be extremely helpful and useful for people who have full hearing ability. First of all, it can allow people to understand some of the culture of the hearing impaired community. In general, it is always good to have an understanding of diverse groups of people. In addition, a time could come when understanding hearing impaired culture and ASL would be beneficial, such as meeting a new person who is hearing impaired, or even having a family member who has lost their hearing or was born without it. %0a%3c %0a%3c Despite this, only about 1.5%25 of public high schools around the country offer any type of ASL programs in class. This is only a tenth of the number of schools which offer French, although there are about 4 fluent French speakers for every ASL speaker in the U.S. Additionally, many programs teach basic signing but do not discuss hearing impaired culture or history in the same way that other foreign language programs do. At the moment, ASL seems to be on the rise, with both the number of speakers and the number of schools teaching the language reportedly having increased over the past decade.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c You must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a